  1. Show that the properties of least squares estimators are satisfied using the following definitions.

\[ \hat{\beta} = (X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T}Y \] \[ \hat{Y} = X\hat{\beta} = X(X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T}Y = HY\] \[ \hat{\varepsilon} = Y - \hat{Y} = (I - H) Y\]

Important notes:

Given that \(H\) is symmetric, then \[ H = H^{T} \] and, \[ HH = (X(X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T})(X(X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T}) = X(X^{T}X)^{-1}(X^{T}X)(X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T} = X(X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T} = H \]

Least Squares Properties

  1. \(1^{T}(I-H)Y = 0\)
  2. \(1^{T}Y = 1^{T}\hat{Y}\)
  3. \(X^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = 0\)
  4. \(\hat{Y}^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = 0\)

Demonstrations:

  • \(1^{T}(I-H)Y = 0\)

Proof, \[ 1^{T}(I-H)Y = (1^{T}I-1^{T}H)Y \] \[ 1^{T}(I-H)Y = (1^{T}-1^{T})Y \] \[ 1^{T}(I-H)Y = 0Y \] \[ 1^{T}(I-H)Y = 0 \square \] * \(1^{T}Y = 1^{T}\hat{Y}\)

Proof,

\[ 1^{T}\hat{Y} = 1^{T}HY \] \[ 1^{T}\hat{Y} = (H^{T}1)^{T}Y \] \[ 1^{T}\hat{Y} = (H1)^{T}Y \] \[ 1^{T}\hat{Y} = 1^{T}Y \square\]

  • \(X^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = 0\)

Proof,

\[ X^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = X^{T}(Y - \hat{Y})\] \[ X^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = X^{T}(Y - HY)\] \[ X^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = X^{T}Y - X^{T}HY\] \[ X^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = X^{T}Y - X^{T}X(X^{T}X)^{-1}X^{T}Y\] \[ X^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = X^{T}Y - X^{T}Y\] \[ X^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = 0 \square\]

  • \(\hat{Y}^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = 0\)

Proof,

\[\hat{Y}^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = (HY)^{T}(I - H)Y\] \[\hat{Y}^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = Y^{T}H(Y - HY)\] \[\hat{Y}^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = Y^{T}HY - Y^{T}HHY\] \[\hat{Y}^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = Y^{T}HY - Y^{T}HY\] \[\hat{Y}^{T}\hat{\varepsilon} = 0\square\]

  1. Given the response variable \(y\) and the covariates \(x2\) and \(x3\) in the dataset Transform_V2.txt data set, check if is necessary to transform any variable and the residual graphs to show that the transformed model is correct.
transformdata = read.csv("../Datasets/Transform_V2.txt", sep = "\t")

ggpairs(transformdata[,c(1,3,4)])

From the above plot, we could improve the linearity of y and x2 by transforming x2.

transformdata2 = transformdata 
transformdata2$x2 = sqrt(transformdata2$x2)

ggpairs(transformdata2[,c(1,3,4)])

Transforming x2 by apply a square root improve the linearity of the relationship.

model_t1 = lm(y ~ x2 + x3, transformdata)
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model_t1)

Diagnostic Plots for Original Linear Model 

model_t2 = lm(y ~ x2 + x3, transformdata2)
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model_t2)

Diagnostic Plot for Transformed Linear Model

We see that this transformation also improved the variance of the residuals.

  1. Given the response variable \(y\) and the covariates \(x1\) and \(x2\) in the dataset Transform2_V2.txt data set, check if is necessary to transform any variable and the residual graphs to show that the transformed model is correct.
transformdata = read.csv("../Datasets/Transform2_V2.txt", sep = "\t")

ggpairs(transformdata)

We can improve the linearity of both relationships (y ~ x1, y ~ x2). For this we’ll use the boxcox method.

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
transformdata2 = transformdata 

boxcox(lm(y2 ~ x1, transformdata2), lambda = seq(-1.5,-0.5, 0.01))
boxcox(lm(y2 ~ x2, transformdata2), lambda = seq(-1.5,-0.5, 0.01))

From the plots above we get that the best possible \(\lambda\) for both is near -1.

So we transform both variables as follows,

transformdata2 = transformdata 
transformdata2$x1 = (transformdata2$x1^(-1) - 1)/(-1)
transformdata2$x2 = (transformdata2$x2^(-1) - 1)/(-1)

ggpairs(transformdata2)

Comparing to the previous plots, there is an improvement in the linearty of both relationships.

model_t1 = lm(y2 ~ x1 + x2, transformdata)
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model_t1)

Diagnostic Plots for Original Linear Model 

model_t2 = lm(y2 ~ x1 + x2, transformdata2)
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model_t2)

Diagnostic Plot for Transformed Linear Model

We see that this transformation also improved the variance of the residuals.

  1. Calculate the value of \(R^{2}\) and \(R^{2}_{a}\) for model fit.ridge and compare them with the result of modall (modall = lm(hwfat ~ .))
library(glmnet)
x = model.matrix(hwfat ~ .-1, bodyfat)
fit.ridge = glmnet(x, bodyfat$hwfat, alpha = 0)
cv.out = cv.glmnet(x, bodyfat$hwfat, alpha = 0)

lambda_opt = cv.out$lambda.min
predicted = predict(fit.ridge, s = lambda_opt, newx= x)


SSE = sum((predicted - bodyfat$hwfat)^2)
SST = sum((bodyfat$hwfat - mean(bodyfat$hwfat))^2)
n = nrow(bodyfat)
k = ncol(bodyfat)

ridge_rsquared = 1 - SSE/SST
ridge_adj_rsquared = 1 - (SSE/(n-k-1))/(SST/(n-1))

ridge_rsquared
## [1] 0.887387
ridge_adj_rsquared
## [1] 0.8761257

summary(modall)$r.squared

summary(modall)$adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.8826699

When comparing both set of values for the model, we can see that both are larger for the linear model.

\[ R^{2}_{lm} > R^{2}_{ridge} \] \[ R^{2}_{a-lm} > R^{2}_{a-ridge} \]
